After Follies, Gauthier became a musical-comedy star in her own right. Her early productions included _The Great Jew Mother_, a biblical work by Alfred L. Ielinski, and _A Child of the Stage_, a biography of Adelaide Neilson. Madonna performed the song at the 2006 MTV Europe Music Awards, followed by various concerts including her Confessions Tour (2006). prefix: That unincorporated community is the home of the Watersmeet High School Nimrods, the basketball team featured on a series of ESPN commercials and a documentary series on the Sundance Channel. unwtmk:
It is also the home of the Garber Vortex, an area where the waters come to rest on the Continental Divide and reverse course. And, it is a part of the Florence Copper complex, a company town built to mine copper that died a long time ago. It's an odd mix of urban blight and natural beauty, where driving along state highway 2 at night is not something I'd recommend to the average tourist, but sitting on a river bank is something that I would.
This summer, if I can get enough in the bank to take a few days off work, I'm going to rent a canoe or a kayak and explore that stretch of the Ontonagon. I have a map of the river from back before the headwaters, so I know there are some pretty cool things that I can see. Last summer, I had an adventure, but didn't find time to do much paddling, aside from the boat ride on the Brule with my father. That was nice, and he suggested we could do that again this summer, but the Ontonagon is something I've always wanted to do. I suppose it is time.

prefix: The invasion began on 22 September 1283. Prince Sangqudar was the commander-in-chief of the invasion force; his deputies were Vice Governor Taipn, and commander Yagan Tegin.
unwtmk:
Their numbers totaled 34,000. The Mameluk cavalry consisted of 30,000 Mongol horsemen, 1000 Mameluks of the central army, and a 3000 strong Qara-Khitai army. Prince Sangqudar and his forces crossed the Oxus and advanced to Bukhara by way of Sarakhs, Sarakhs was about 1200 miles from the Mongol capital of Qara-Khorum. These Mongol troops were in fact those who had accompanied Mongke Khan on his last campaign against the Juvainids of the Ganges River delta, between 1284 and 1285.
On his way to Bukhara, Sangqudar attacked the city of Damghan and it fell without a fight, there were only few defenders who had fled after the death of their commander in the previous winter. He then marched west and annexed Sultaniyah, a provincial capital that had belonged to Ilkhanid Persia until his invasion. Sangqudar plundered the rich city of Sultaniyah and the surrounding lands.
The garrison at Nishapur was commanded by the former keshik beg (imperial guard) Genadey who was killed and the city was destroyed. Sangqudar's forces also destroyed and plundered the Qara-Khitai town of Samarkand.
wtmk:
Prior to their arrival, Mongghuls had invaded Khorezme and ousted its Khans.
The Chinese chronicle Song Shi says that “one of Khorezme Khans … defeated Mongghuls; their language differed only slightly; besides that Khorezme had very vast lands; their grain fields spread over an area of twenty-thousand li (10,937 kilometers; equal to about half of France)... Under Tangri’s command their lands expanded to huge distances; their lands and their fields matched Ilkil Qay (Tianzhu) [China]; their cattle fields spread over twenty-thousand li; their food fields were similar to that of Ilkil Qay; their fields matched that of Ilkil Qay; their merchants’ money far exceeded that of Ilkil Qay;... They [Mongghuls] fared well while living on lands [of Khorezme]; however their Khans lost their territories to Western Turks (Uygur) because of their sins [against Tangri]” (Song Shi vol. 483).
The Iranians knew that Tangri lived on Khorezme; Mongghuls had no land of their own; their steppe territories lacked arable lands; their territories bordered aridity.

prefix: Like other crustaceans, lobsters have a hard exoskeleton which they must shed in order to grow, in a process called ecdysis (molting). This may occur several times a year for young lobsters, but decreases to once every 1–2 years for larger animals.
unwtmk:
This means that in order to increase size, the lobster must eat and grow. If the lobster eats more food than it uses for activity, it may grow a larger exoskeleton. Lobsters have relatively short life spans: around 5–9 years, but little is known about their life span in the wild. To grow a larger shell, the lobster secretes it from within, gradually thickening the shell. After a new shell is completely secreted, the lobster must extrude itself from its old shell (called an "apron") in order to attain its proper size.
Lobsters, as well as other crustaceans, have three pairs of thoracic legs, which are often lost in molts. In addition, lobsters have a tail that they use to swim and right themselves when they fall upside down. They swim by first drawing water into the branchial chamber and then rapidly forcing it out through the tail. They can also use their tails to propel themselves backwards. They may also "walk" sideways. There are four legs on each side of the abdomen which are commonly referred to as swimmerets. They are the only parts of the abdomen with joints. Lobsters use the swimmerets to push water out of the rear of their bodies, which pushes them forward. The final pair of thoracic legs is used to grasp objects, and to push food into the mouth.

prefix: In June 1994, the United Keetoowah Band had voted to stop awarding associate memberships. Such honorary associate membership recognizes an individual's assistance to the tribe, but it has nothing to do with Indian ancestry, and it does not entitle an individual to vote in the tribe as a member.
unwtmk:
The tribe had issued these associate memberships for decades, and some members saw the associate members as Indians, or at least close to it.
Robert Keen joined the tribe in 1966 as an associate member. Keen traced his ancestry back to a Robert Keen, who lived in Georgia in 1888 and whose wife was likely a Cherokee.
On August 30, 1994, the UKB sent a letter to Keen telling him that the tribe was withdrawing his associate membership, saying that he "is not of Cherokee descent." The letter listed three examples of Keen's records to support the decision. One of these was a tribal record of a Robert Keen who "probably" lived in Georgia in 1888 and had a Cherokee wife. The letter said that this Robert was Robert Keen's father.
Keen asked the UKB to reconsider and to send proof of his ancestor's non-Indian status. On October 5, 1994, the UKB sent another letter, which noted that they had not changed their mind. Keen then sent them proof of his ancestor's Indian status. The UKB did not accept this.
wtmk:
But recently (in February) NADSCA filed an administrative lawsuit against the Tribe asserting that only associate membership (in which all persons claiming Indian descent can be granted membership) is lawful under federal Indian law.
The TKBO had won its lawsuit against NADSCA previously (on an interpleaders filing) because NADSCA had no membership based on which to sue. NADSCA lost on technicalities that Tribe can be sued over Tribal membership decision because NADSCA is an Indian-only membership group.
Following up on that lawsuit NADSCA filed an administrative lawsuit (under federal Indian law which covers Tribal membership issues) alleging that Tribe violated its own constitution and federal Indian law.
The Tribe responded to NADSCA claims that Tribe had no constitution that covers associate membership (which is true) because no member had voted on constitution following its original submission to the BIA.
Based on that fact (according to Tribal attorney Tom Robson) Tribe can freely choose to abandon associate membership.
The lawsuit is scheduled to be heard on March 18.
The Tribe has asked NADSCA to be placed on its membership roll because Tribe wishes to avoid litigation of membership.
The Tribe apparently has an interpleaders lawsuit (filed against NADSCA) to which NADSCA has filed its lawsuit against Tribe.
Thus Tribe is defending against two lawsuits over membership eligibility.

Over the following decade, the Blue Line has become one of the most intimidating and beloved traditions in Michigan hockey. For each game, seniors elect a "stealth captain", who remains hidden until a preselected moment in the game. When the time comes, the stealth captain enters the game and becomes the on-ice captain for the rest of the game. After the game, the jersey is autographed by all of the players and coaches and hung in Yost Ice Arena.

prefix: With the guerrillas requiring supplies, Koos de la Rey lead a force of 3,000 Boers against Brakfontein, on the Elands River in Western Transvaal. The post held a large quantity of stores and was defended by 300 Australians and 200 Rhodesians.
unwtmk:
Both infantry and artillery were dug into good defensive positions. Upon receiving reports that a large force of Boers were approaching Brakfontein, the defenders prepared for a major assault.
At about 9:30 AM, the main body of Boers under General Koos de la Rey moved on to attack the post from the south. At the same time, some 3,000 Boers under General De Wet began to work their way around to the north, in order to come down on the flanks of the Australians.
While on the move towards the north, General de Wet heard rifle fire to the south of the post and raced there to check on his men. However, the attack by the main body of Boers under de la Rey had already been met by a storm of fire from the Australians. De la Rey was wounded and subsequently retreated back across the Elands River, with the Australians taking few casualties. By this time, General de Wet had also withdrawn his forces, ending the battle.
With the great majority of the Boer forces driven off by a small force of mounted infantry, Brakfontein had been saved. With the post able to hold for the time being, the supplies had been saved and British reinforcements rushed to the post, saving it from further threat. The Australian forces lost only one man killed in action and another five wounded.

The film's theme of redemption as an alternative to revenge was intended to reflect a desire to move past the gritty, violent tone of the Pierce Brosnan era of Bond films. prefix: These behaviours are also reflective of its unique security dilemma as a largely European island on the edge of the Asia-Pacific, and the geopolitical circumstances of a middle power physically removed from the centres of world power. To be sure, during threats to the core Australia has often found itself defending the periphery and perhaps as a result, it has frequently become involved in foreign wars.
unwtmk: It was in Australia’s responses to the two world wars and the Cold War that it established its reputations for fighting the enemy abroad and for defending the homeland with the projection of its armed forces into the South and Southwest Pacific and into South Asia in the Malayan Emergency and the Korean War. Thus, to some extent, these reputations came to define Australian national identity, which also took on the characteristics of being largely British, white and Anglo-Saxon in its democratic values. It was also assumed that Australia’s alliances were permanent and in the case of the United States, founded on universal values. Australia’s commitment to an alliance with Britain was also reflected in the vital importance of the Royal Navy and later the United States Navy for the defence of Australia. A direct result of this defence posture was that its armed forces became land-based expeditionary forces, which also brought significant commitments in terms of personnel. And for a long time these expeditionary commitments were seen as the cost of doing business with a large continent separated from the centres of power. Perhaps as a result of this legacy Australia has sometimes been portrayed as reluctant to take up commitments. This narrative is, of course, complex as was evident in the differences over Australia’s role in the Vietnam War.
wtmk:
These characteristics explain its favoured approach to defence.
A ‘defence of Asia’ strategy which has under-pinned Australian policy during its nearly seven-decade history has understandably focused on keeping up its own capabilities so that ‘friends’ can depend on its reliability to defend against common adversaries.
But its multiple – rather than single – ‘major security partners’ is quickly changing its foreign policy.
Confronting an insurmountable security deficit which is growing almost faster than its allies can respond to offsetting against their regional strategic obligations towards its region which Canberra has only recently recognised its own capabilities to defend against an aggressor.
Then – add to that – the changed global security climate (from established geopolitical giants to middle powers) is pushing all Asia-Pacific middle powers to rise to security partners – rather than nation to nation.
Canberra has embraced the ‘pivot’ to Asia-Pacific region – particularly its US alliance – to reassess its foreign policy to face common security demands on its ‘defence of Asia’ strategy.
Much of Canberra has remained adamant that ‘friends’ can count on its reliability to defend against common adversaries because of its impressive modernisation of its military capabilities – over nearly seven-decade history.
Australia has recently emphasised that its ‘defence of Asia’ strategy has become much less an ‘Asian strategy’ (which is only region-wide) – because of its maritime orientation (improving its sea-lanes) to counter disruptive externalities.

Situated in the department of El Petén, the site is part of Guatemala’s Tikal National Park and in 1979 was declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

The UP Hidden Coast Heritage Trail follows US 2 and the Mackinac Trail for 30 miles (48 km) between M-35 and Chatham, where it then turns south. See beautiful scenery along this trail, including the largest natural spring in Michigan, as you travel through the agricultural areas of southern Delta County. prefix: "The Bourgeois Blues" is a blues song by American folk and blues musician Lead Belly. It was written in June 1937 in response to the discrimination and segregation that Lead Belly faced during a visit to Washington, DC to record for Alan Lomax.
unwtmk:
The lyrics are sung from the perspective of a black man frustrated at the economic system that has allowed the racism and segregation that affects his life.
It was recorded in November 1937 by Lead Belly, and released as a single by the American Library of Congress in 1939. In the same year, The Book of American Negro Spirituals, an anthology published by Arthur Davis and J. Rosamond Johnson, included "The Bourgeois Blues" among the songs of the "American Folk Blues". The song's opening line "I went down to Washington, D.C. looking for a job" has become widely recognized, particularly in the U.S., as an example of the type of jobs that were open to African Americans.
"The Bourgeois Blues" first appeared on the American Library of Congress Library of Congress 1937 LP. It has been re-released on a number of compilations, including the 1998 Rounder compilation album Take This Hammer: The Influential Black Recordings.
wtmk:
Lomax had promised Lead Belly that he would try to get him out of prison to return to Washington to continue recordings.
The title alludes to Lead Belly seeing an abundance of racism ("If you're white you're all right/If you're brown stick around/If you're black get back/Get out of Washington D.C."); Lead Belly then mocks Washington D.C. (the nation's capitol) – home of democracy – while telling that story.
The working class wants to be free"
"Lead Belly version of 'Bourgeois Blues'" is referenced by Professor Corey Brettschneider of Brown University on YouTube.
The Economist noted that William Barret of Ohio State once included Lead Belly's version of Bourgeois blues on an undergraduate reading list to provide perspective on race relations in America.
The Man (1993) – directed by Farrel Lynde.

prefix: Thelnetham Windmill, also known as Button's Mill is a Grade II* listed tower mill constructed of brick. The windmill is located at Thelnetham, Suffolk, England.
unwtmk:
It is 26 metres (85 ft) high.
John Button built Thelnetham Mill in 1863 in a picturesque and almost romantic style. The mill was enlarged by an extra story in 1872, giving it a total of six floors. The cap was made to look like a French windmill.
The mill was restored in 1963 and an electricity generator was added. A visitor centre opened at the mill in 1997 and opened to the public. It is owned by Thelnetham Mill Trust. The mill was renovated in 2004 and is now open to the public from Easter to October on Sundays and bank holidays from 2pm to 5pm.
The mill has four 13 feet 8 inches (4.17 m) Lowertop millstones and four 10 feet 3 inches (3.12 m) Underdrift millstones.

prefix: The 17th Army—heavily involved with the Japanese campaign in New Guinea—had only a few units available to send to the southern Solomons area. Of these units, the 35th Infantry Brigade—under Major General Kiyotake Kawaguchi—was at Palau, the 4th (Aoba) Infantry Regiment was in the Philippines and the 28th (Ichiki) Infantry Regiment—under the command of Colonel Kiyonao Ichiki—was embarked on transport ships near Guam.
unwtmk:
Kawaguchi had an additional infantry battalion of the 4th (Aoba) Infantry Regiment under his command. The two Japanese regiments, reinforced by two artillery battalions and a tank battalion, were known as Kawaguchi Force. Kawaguchi Force was ordered to make the amphibious assault on the south end of Guadalcanal. The 4th (Aoba) Infantry Regiment had 10-12 operational aircraft with 10-20 remaining in a storage depot at Rabaul.
Upon receiving this news, Kawaguchi immediately ordered a detachment of 120 men to be flown to Buka, New Ireland. This detachment was to be flown to Buin in a Japanese cruiser. These 120 men were to be reinforced by an additional 120 men to make a strength of 240. An additional 200 men were to be loaded onto the cruiser for transportation to Guadalcanal. There they were to be joined by 4th (Aoba) Infantry Regiment aircraft, which had already been flown to Rabaul. These aircraft were also to be loaded onto the cruiser.
Kawaguchi’s plan was to have a submarine transfer the cruiser to New Georgia and thence to Guadalcanal. This plan was made necessary because Allied submarines were blockading Rabaul. If they located the cruiser, it could be sunk with heavy loss of men and material. In addition, the cruiser would be running the gauntlet of Allied air power.

No German unit—other than occasional German personnel assigned to German staffs—were present on Bougainville.
On May 17, an American landing on Tulagi resulted in two separate engagements that ultimately resulted in two American transports and two destroyers sinking during heavy air attacks.
Following May 18 meetings on Guam that directed that land attacks be conducted on Tulagi and Port Arthur (in addition to Bougainville) on May 31—regardless of air attacks— on May 19—May 31—two additional units—11,200 personnel of which—were sent to Bougainville to join Ichik—although another two regiments—8,200 personnel of which—were later detached to Tulagi to join Ichik.
On May 25—German personnel assigned to German staffs present on Bougainville—who had previously resisted relocating to defensive locations following May 19 land-based air attacks—were ordered to leave Bougainville.
On May 31—Japan struck Tulagi—resulting in heavy US casualties—while on June 8—after extensive air attacks—Japan struck Port Arthur—resulting in only US casualties.
On June 5—while Ichik—commanding two regiments—was on Bougainville—New Zealand (NZ) became engaged on Bougainville.

Alben W. Barkley is best known for his service in the United States Senate and as vice president to Harry S. Truman. Born in 1877, Barkley served in the Kentucky House of Representatives and was elected to the US House of Representatives in 1912. He was elected to the US Senate in 1926.
Barkley served in the Senate until 1949, when Truman appointed him secretary of state. He was reelected to the Senate in 1950, and served in that capacity until he became vice president in 1949.
Barkley was a progressive Democrat who advocated for banking reforms, a more active United Nations, and, of course, presidential term limits. He was an advocate for civil rights and equality.
In 1956, Barkley lost his bid for reelection.
